article.headline: Lights out: Storm send Liberty to 10th straight loss
article.linkText: Lights out: Storm send Liberty to 10th straight loss
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- The Seattle Storm took advantage of the
struggling and shorthanded New York Liberty and cruised to their
biggest win of the season.

Iziane Castro Marques scored a career-high 26 points and Lauren
Jackson added 18 points and nine rebounds to lead the Storm to a
91-54 victory Saturday night, handing the Liberty their
franchise-worst 10th straight loss and their largest margin of
defeat ever.

"It was really unthinkable, a good game," said Castro Marques,
who shot 10 for 12 from the field. "I tried to bring my best."

Betty Lennox had 14 points -- all in the first half -- and Sue
Bird added 10 for Seattle (12-12), which won for the second time in
six games. The Storm began the day tied with San Antonio for fourth
place in the Western Conference, a half-game ahead of Phoenix.

"It was very important because we had three losses, so we
really need to get back on track if you want to make the
playoffs," Castro Marques said. "We're right there, but everybody
else is right there, too. So if you want to do it, you have to come
up with big wins now."

Erin Thorn scored 19 points for the Liberty (4-19), who set the
franchise record for losses in a season and did it in a big way.
New York was beaten by a previous franchise-record 35 points twice
earlier this season.

"We just came out slow, let them hit shots early and they got
on a run," Thorn said. "They're a great shooting team, and if you
let them get open shots early it's hard to come back."

New York was without All-Star guard Becky Hammon and center
Kelly Schumacher. Hammon missed her fifth straight game with a
sprained left ankle, and Schumacher is out for the season after
spraining the medial collateral ligament in her right knee in the
opening minute of a loss at Sacramento on Thursday.

Lennox scored 12 points in the first quarter as Seattle
outscored New York 24-3 over the final 7:12 of the period and took
a 30-8 lead. Jackson had eight points in the second, including two
3-pointers, as the Storm stretched their lead to 50-23 at halftime.

This effort topped a 30-point win over San Antonio on June 23.

"We came out and jumped on them early," Bird said. "We got
some stops and were able to run. When we are in transition, that is
when we are at our best."

Seattle shot a season-high 57 percent (39 for 68) and held New
York to 34 percent (19 for 56).

Thorn was 6 for 9, including 4 for 5 on 3s, and finished one
point short of her career high that was set in the loss at
Sacramento.

"The big picture is the 'W' and we didn't get it, so it's
frustrating," Thorn said. "It's always frustrating not to be
hitting shots and not to be executing like we can."

Schumacher, playing in her first season with New York after four
years in Indiana, was leading the Liberty with 5.5 rebounds and 1.2
blocks per game.

The Liberty, 101-43 at home coming into the season, dropped to
2-9 at Madison Square Garden. Sixth-place New York dropped eight
games behind Washington for the fourth and final playoff spot in
the East, with 11 games remaining for both teams.
